# Sticky app header (default)

Hub apps keep the **title/actions header pinned** while body content scrolls.

## Default pattern

1. Wrap the app header and the progress host in `.hub-sticky-chrome` (see `rayenz-hub/shared/hub-app-chrome.css`).
2. Header element uses the app class (`.ds-header`, `.dr-header`, `.or-header`, `.site-header`).
3. Scrollable content lives **below** the sticky chrome (e.g. `.ds-body`, `.dr-body`, `.or-body`, dailies collapsibles).
4. New apps must use this wrapper unless added to **Documented overrides** first.

```html
<div class="hub-sticky-chrome">
   <header class="ds-header">…</header>
   <div class="hub-progress-host" id="ds-progress-host"></div>
</div>
<div class="ds-body">…</div>
```

Do **not** use `position: fixed` for app headers unless listed under **Documented overrides**.

## Overrides

To skip `.hub-sticky-chrome` or use a non-sticky header (full-bleed layout, embedded iframe, etc.):

1. Add a row under **Documented overrides** below **in the same change** as the code.
2. Use the standard row format. Unlisted deviations are not allowed.

Row format:

`- **{App}** — \`{file or symbol}\` — {what uses non-default pattern} — {why} (added: YYYY-MM-DD)`

## Documented overrides

_(none)_

## Enforcement

- New Hub apps must use `.hub-sticky-chrome` unless listed above.
- New override: edit this `.mdc` file in the same PR; do not add silent exceptions in code only.
- When reviewing diffs under `apps/**`, check header layout against **Documented overrides**.
